Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)

# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.next = next
class Solution:
    def removeNodes(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:
        head = self.reverse(head)
        curr = head
        max_val = head.val
        while curr and curr.next:
            if curr.next.val < max_val:
                curr.next = curr.next.next
            else: 
                curr = curr.next
                max_val = curr.val

        return self.reverse(head)
        
        
        
    def reverse(self, head):
        prev = None
        curr = head

        while curr:
            nxt = curr.next
            curr.next = prev
            prev = curr
            curr = nxt

        return prev




Why reverse the linked list?

Because the problem asks:
Remove nodes that have a GREATER value somewhere to the RIGHT
But in a normal linked list traversal:
you can only easily move left → right
You cannot efficiently look ahead to all future nodes

Reverse the list:

8 -> 3 -> 13 -> 2 -> 5

Now think carefully:

Original question:

Is there a greater node to my RIGHT?

After reversing:

Those "right-side" nodes become LEFT-side nodes

Now during traversal:

You already visited them

So you only need:

maximum value seen so far
